00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:13.200
[Guest 2]: there are a few which have done in-depth study on this and the idea is that

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:17.720
[Guest 2]: Women are considered to be

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:23.480
[Guest 2]: Income earners until unless the household income is has reached a certain point beyond which

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:26.200
[Guest 2]: they expect women to be

00:07:26.520 --> 00:07:29.880
[Guest 2]: Contributing to the household chores which are considered to be the women

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:34.000
[Amit Varma]: So basically what you're saying is that in really poor families, there's no choice

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:39.080
[Amit Varma]: They have to let the woman work because they need the income but the moment she reaches a level where household reaches an income

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:42.040
[Guest 2]: They they believe that the woman can get back

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:46.040
[Guest 1]: What you're saying is there's something that we call a double burden, right?

00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:48.320
[Guest 1]: So generally women who are working have to do work

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:53.280
[Guest 1]: But they also have to come back and cook and clean and take care of their kids and all of that

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:58.600
[Guest 1]: What you're saying is after a certain point they're saying we will take away the double burden from you

00:07:58.600 --> 00:08:01.200
[Guest 1]: You don't go to work you stay at home. Is that right?

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:05.280
[Guest 2]: Yeah, exactly and the priority that your priority is not to have that career

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:08.160
[Guest 2]: Your priority is to ensure that the household runs fine

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:09.720
[Guest 2]: so then therefore

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:15.920
[Guest 2]: It makes sense for them that as soon as the household reaches a point where you can stay back home your priority shifts to taking

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:18.440
[Amit Varma]: Care of everything that is and the way you put it Hamsini

00:08:18.440 --> 00:08:23.640
[Amit Varma]: It almost sounds like you know, it's a patriarchy's way of empowering women that you have a double burden even take one

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:31.640
[Guest 3]: The unpaid care work that women have to do so take care of the children take care of the men at home

00:08:32.040 --> 00:08:35.240
[Guest 3]: Cook clean. It's all unpaid and it's taken for granted

00:08:35.240 --> 00:08:39.280
[Amit Varma]: So the man will take the credit for you know, all the capital he brings home

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:46.120
[Guest 3]: But the woman's capital is simply not considered. It's just because how do you put money to this? How how much is it worth?

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:49.760
[Guest 2]: I have a base idea of that actually

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:56.760
[Guest 2]: So, um, if you actually do a math of how much do you pay a cook? How much do you pay your if to a laundry person?

00:08:56.760 --> 00:08:59.480
[Guest 2]: How much do you pay the cleaning lady?

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:05.560
[Guest 2]: How much do you pay all of these people who help run your household and as someone who's been living in a city alone?

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:09.960
[Guest 2]: I I do pay people for all of these stuff that my mom used to do back home, right?

00:09:10.440 --> 00:09:15.360
[Guest 2]: So now I know that this is the amount of money at least that my mom deserves for every monthly

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:22.320
[Guest 2]: Monthly amount she spends on doing this work, right? So a lot of countries have actually tried to come up with a

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:25.040
[Guest 2]: base figure for unpaid care

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:30.640
[Guest 2]: The problem with that is that even though it's acknowledged no one really pays

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:31.880
[Amit Varma]: There's no real value to it

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:37.320
